{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e44e9cf-7a2c-4c6f-8ab7-f689cf52e7d8","content":"This isn't covered in the current repository. Here's the general guidance from my knowledge:\n\n**On macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n2. **Check macOS crash reports** — look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` system-wide) for `.ips` / `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n3. **Use `/cores/`** — macOS writes core files to `/cores/core.<pid>` (ensure the directory exists and is writable: `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`).\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS SIP or privacy settings may block core dumps. You can check with `sysctl kern.coredump` (should be `1`).\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT binaries include native symbols, so `lldb` can often provide usable stack traces directly from the core file without additional symbol files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13edd13e-cded-4cdf-a009-18039e51fb68","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't contain relevant documentation about this topic. Let me answer from my general knowledge about macOS crash dumps and NativeAOT.","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"CB14:3DEB8E:1E14DE5:2160278:6A052A31"},"id":"7de3ff6f-9f95-41c3-8551-4ced8c92f570","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:49:47.630Z","parentId":"af8c3d49-56d5-4f59-8c4e-5e2a62508711"}
